Naturally, this is only a plausible sketch, and other conceivable executions of the same basic idea come to mind;
40 nonetheless, I believe the main point of this discussion should be clear: even in imperatives, which, unlike CI and SCLI sentences, do seem to require verb movement to the (highest layer of the) Comp area, there is evidence that verb related displacements to lower layers of the left periphery can take the shape of (Remnant) Phrasal Movement. Without that assumption it is difficult to see how all the possible clitic sequences of French positive imperatives could be derived syntactically.
41 The plausibility of our Remnant Movement approach to SCLI and CI is thus enhanced by the syntax of clitics in French imperatives.

(85)
a. -t- is a morphological enclitic; therefore, as a tense morpheme, it must be right adjacent to a finite verb at PF.
b. -t- is a deficient morpheme at PF, i.e., it cannot in and of itself bear word-final stress; it must therefore be left adjacent to a term that can play the part of an additional stress bearing suffix;
